Another enzyme, known as sheddase, disassembles the cyto-structured domain of ACE2 from across the membrane structure, and releases the soluble protein into the blood and eventually discharges it into the urine.
ACE2 exists in most organs: ACE2 is attached to a cell membrane, mainly a lung type II pulmonary cell, intestinal peritoneal cells, arteries and vein internal cells of most organs, and arterial smooth muscle cells.
